\subsection{Inductive bias}

What is inductive bias?

-   An assumption that allows the model to make predictions about
    never-seen data.
-   All models carry one form of an inductive bias or other.
    -   i.e.: linear model, nonlinear model, type of non-linearity\...

Why do we need it?

-   Data is expensive to gather or generate.
-   Data is sparse - usually, we observe only a sample of the true data
    population.
-   Generalization is *necessary* for both academic and industrial use
    of (deep) models.

\subsection{Inductive bias in NNs}

\aligncenter{\includepng{\diagramsDir/convnets/ferenc}{900px}}


-   Common to all NNs
    -   Layered feature maps</li></ul>
        -   Nodes within a layer are assumed never to interact</li></ul></ul>
        -   Inputs are processed on an directed acyclic graph</li></ul></ul>    
    -   Gradient descent</li></ul>
        -   Preference for models trainable by gradient</li></ul></ul>
        -   <pp>descent given the chosen initializer</pp>
        -   <pp>Recall week 2: Optimization and Stochastic Gradient Descent</pp>

-   Layer-specific inductive biases - relational inductive biases
    -   **Locality: CNNs - preferred model is invariant to spatial translations**
    -   Sequentiality: RNNs - preferred model is invariant to time translations
    -   Arbitrary: Graph NNs - preferred model is invariant to node & edge permutations



\subsection{Inductive bias in NNs}

-   **Plain English:** An inductive bias allows a learning algorithm to
    prioritize one solution (or interpretation) over another,
    independent of the observed data.

-   **Bayesian perspective:** inductive biases are captured by the
    model's prior distribution. In this context, the specific shoice of
    an NN architecture can be seen as an extreme choice of a prior.
    
    $$ \large p(\theta\|X,Y)= \huge
    \frac{p(Y|X,\theta) p(\theta)}{p(Y|X)}$$
    
-   **Technical perspective:** all NN layers can be seen as special
    cases of fully connected layers. Inductive biases are expressed by
    the weight-sharing restrictions that define any given layer type.

\subsection{CNN summary}

-   A convolutional layer is defined by
    -   **Kernel:** dimensions, channels (count)
    -   **Application rule:** stride, padding
    -   **Parameters:** weights, biases
-   Convolutions tend to over-focus on texture
    -   Using small (3x3) kernels learning from textures easier than
        learning from large-scale structures
    -   Most networks have inductive bias in favour of predicting from
        texture
    -   Many adversarial methods are based on this inductive bias
        (adding jitter, changing texture)

    -   Execution on Tegra GPU
    -   Reported: parameters and latency


-   Layer types
    -   Feed-forward layers (fully connected)
    -   Convolutional layers and pooling layers
    -   Other: dropout and softmax 

-   Convolution benefits:
    -   Helps generalization
    -   Lowers memory requirements


-   No free lunch
    -   Weight sharing does not lower MACs
    -   Pooling is as costly as a simple convolution
